Exercise 8: Implementing the Strategy Pattern

## Aim

To implement the Strategy Design Pattern for a payment system that allows different payment methods to be selected and used at runtime.

## Project Name

StrategyPatternExample

## Project Structure

```text
StrategyPatternExample
│
├── PaymentStrategy.java
├── CreditCardPayment.java
├── PayPalPayment.java
├── PaymentContext.java
└── StrategyTest.java
```

## 1. Define Strategy Interface

### PaymentStrategy.java

```java
public interface PaymentStrategy {
    void pay(double amount);
}
```

## 2. Implement Concrete Strategies

### CreditCardPayment.java

```java
public class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentStrategy {

    @Override
    public void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid Rs." + amount + " using Credit Card");
    }
}
```

### PayPalPayment.java

```java
public class PayPalPayment implements PaymentStrategy {

    @Override
    public void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid Rs." + amount + " using PayPal");
    }
}
```

## 3. Implement Context Class

### PaymentContext.java

```java
public class PaymentContext {

    private PaymentStrategy paymentStrategy;

    public void setPaymentStrategy(PaymentStrategy paymentStrategy) {
        this.paymentStrategy = paymentStrategy;
    }

    public void executePayment(double amount) {
        paymentStrategy.pay(amount);
    }
}
```

## 4. Test the Strategy Pattern

### StrategyTest.java

```java
public class StrategyTest {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        PaymentContext context = new PaymentContext();

        context.setPaymentStrategy(new CreditCardPayment());
        context.executePayment(5000);

        context.setPaymentStrategy(new PayPalPayment());
        context.executePayment(2500);
    }
}
```

## Output

```text
Paid Rs.5000.0 using Credit Card
Paid Rs.2500.0 using PayPal
```

## Working

1. The `PaymentStrategy` interface defines the common `pay()` method.
2. `CreditCardPayment` and `PayPalPayment` are concrete strategy classes implementing different payment methods.
3. `PaymentContext` maintains a reference to a `PaymentStrategy`.
4. The strategy can be changed at runtime using the `setPaymentStrategy()` method.
5. The `executePayment()` method delegates the payment operation to the selected strategy.
6. The client can switch between payment methods without modifying the context class.

## Advantages of Strategy Pattern

1. Encapsulates different algorithms in separate classes.
2. Allows runtime selection of algorithms.
3. Promotes the Open-Closed Principle.
4. Eliminates complex conditional statements.
5. Improves flexibility and maintainability.

## Conclusion

The Strategy Pattern was successfully implemented using a common PaymentStrategy interface and multiple payment method implementations. The PaymentContext class dynamically selects and executes the desired payment strategy at runtime. This approach provides flexibility, scalability, and maintainability while allowing easy addition of new payment methods in the future.
